class TreeNode {
    constructor(val) {
        this.val = val;
        this.left = this.right = null;
    }
}

function isCompleteTree(root) {
    if (!root) return true;

    let queue = [root];
    let hasGap = false;
    while (queue.length) {
        let node = queue.shift();
        if (node.left) {
            if (hasGap) return false;
            queue.push(node.left);
        } else {
            hasGap = true;
        }
        if (node.right) {
            if (hasGap) return false;
            queue.push(node.right);
        } else {
            hasGap = true;
        }
    }
    return true;
}
```

    To check if the given binary tree is a complete binary tree, we can use a method called Breadth First Search (BFS) or level-order traversal.

1. Start by creating a queue and adding the root node to it.
2. Then, use a loop to iterate through nodes in the queue. For each node, dequeue it, and enqueue its left and right children (if any) in the order they appear.
3. Keep iterating until you find a node with no left child or right child.
4. After that, check if all remaining nodes in the queue also have no children. If yes, then the given tree is a complete binary tree. Otherwise, it's not.

The time complexity of this algorithm is O(n), where n is the number of nodes in the binary tree, as each node is visited once.

